04404nam a22006495i 9781501736896DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20191992nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017368967 a10.7591/97815017368962doi  a(DE-B1597)545832  a(OCoLC)1198930931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0840002bisacsh1 aKemper, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Presence of the Past :bChronicles, Politics, and Culture in Sinhala Life /cSteven Kemper. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Wilder House series in politics, history, and culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Past Uses of the Past -- t2. Heroic Leaders and Discourses of Unity -- t3. Colonial Constructions of the Past -- t4. Contesting the Past -- t5. Races and Places -- t6. An Elected Government Invokes the Past -- t7. Nationalist Discourse -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTracing the evolution of an ancient but ongoing Sri Lankan chronicle, Steven Kemper deepens our understanding of the complex role of the historical past in the rise of nationalist movements. Kemper focuses in particular on the Mahavamsa, a Buddhist historical narrative which has been periodically extended over the last fourteen centuries, most recently in 1977 when President Jayewardene assembled a committee of scholars, bureaucrats, and monks to bring the chronicle up to date.Kemper is concerned both with the development of Sinhala national identity and with the impact of historical consciousness in Sri Lankan culture and political life today. He discusses Sri Lankan party politics, ethnic conflict between Sinhala Buddhists and the Tamil minority, and political exchanges between the state, the monkhood, and the laity. Kemper argues that in Sri Lanka the past is made tangible through a set of social practices of genuine historical antiquity—chroniclekeeping, maintaining sacred places, and venerating heroes; and that the nationalist invocation of the past gathers its force from the way present-day circumstances impose new meanings on these practices.By taking up the contention that Sinhala nationalism antedates the rise of nationalist movements in Europe by over a thousand years, Kemper's analysis offers challenging implications for our interpretation of nationalism as a modern European phenomenon. Anthropologists specializing in political development, historical anthropology, and oral and popular traditions; historians of South Asia; political scientists concerned with ethnic conflict; and others interested in the intersection of politics and religion will welcome The Presence of the Past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aAmerican Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173689640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501736896423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501736896/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK